2023: Time to DISRUPT. 💥
•
Phew! What a year. Presented at my first conference, signed on for two more, enjoyed new partnerships, and changed school districts. Oh! I guess I also made the news for holding a coffee mug. Scandalous! I wanted to share some of my reflections from this year. 
•
📖 GROWTH over CONTROL. Something that’s been sitting on my mind during these “reading wars” and attacks on LGBTQ educators is: Are we in a climate of control? Or a climate of feedback, growth, and empathy? Remember, a curriculum does not instruct. Fight for your right to give students what they need. Are you valued? Are you trusted? Families and educators deserve a climate that welcomes questions, push-backs, and alternative thinking. After all, half a million educators resigned last year. More of the same is a slippery slope. 
•
🍸 DISRUPT THE COMFORT. Colleagues of mine know that I’m a staunch advocate for choices that prioritize children. This takes unlearning and commitment to changing broken systems and harmful ways of thinking. I’m not here to tone myself down or fit to a mold. If you are uncomfortable with structured literacy at the forefront in K to 2 classrooms, ask yourself why that might be. If you are uncomfortable with an LGBTQ+ educator normalizing their existence in a diverse world - why is that? How can you grow from that discomfort? •
•
💫 EXPERIENCE does not equal COMPETENCY. To my principal friends, coach friends, specialist friends, new teacher friends: Your voice and opinions matter. Your questions matter. Your celebrations and milestones matter. Do not discredit your ideas because a colleague has been “doing it longer.” Speak up for yourself. Speak up for kids. Speak up for families. •
•
🤍 I have to thank the thousands of people that fought back in solidarity when I was attacked this past July. Who knew that being a gay reading teacher means you need police surveillance outside of your house?! While I don’t believe there needs to be a lesson attached to trauma, I do think I learned the importance of protecting my peace. •
•
So, what will you disrupt with me in 2023?! What peace will you be protecting?! I’m grateful for you all. Happy New Year. 💫

📚 Family Literacy Week 💫

January 23-27! I want to thank @myliteracyspace for inviting me to join some fabulous individuals in sharing 5 days of picture books and literacy tips. 

Today’s book? Danbi Leads the School Parade. Considering how difficult it can be to join a new club, community, class, or environment — this book is perfect for building your classroom community with identity at the forefront. 

Some questions I like to ask prior to reading: 
💫 What’s something that makes you special? 
💫 When do you feel most like yourself? 
💫 What is identity? 
💫 When have you learned something from someone else? What was it, and why do you remember it? 

After we read, we talk about Danbi’s character traits and why celebrating her identity was so important to her happiness. 
Then, we make Identity Webs with pictures and images that represent our background, interests, and characteristics. 

Follow these amazing accounts for a picture book with a literacy idea for you to use in your classroom, homeschool learning space, therapy room, or wherever you cuddle up with a kiddo for a read aloud.

It’s me, hi! 💫 

About 10k of you are new here, so I thought I’d catch you up and do a little introduction. Welcome! 

🍎 I’m entering my 8th year of teaching. Frequent nicknames include “that punctuation guy”, “that phonics guy”, or “the guy from those videos.” 😂 I’ve taught Pre-K, 3rd, 2nd, and 1st. 

🏳️‍🌈 I’ve dragged across the front page news for existing as an LGBTQ+ teacher, so my skin has gotten pretty thick. The death threats and anonymous hate mail are getting so old and tired. Anyway. This is a page where you will see advocacy and complete authenticity. No human has more value than another, so you’ll see me fighting for basic human decency more than ever before. Inclusion is a verb. 

📚 The work I do is not only rooted in structured literacy methods, but also a combination of mind and body. My gestures and motions are very carefully selected to promote mastery of articulation, formation, and location/frequency. 

🫖 I’ve faced enough adversity in this field to know when it’s narcissistic vs. for the actual benefit of children. We are no longer entertaining the whole “explicit phonics is boring and takes away student choice.” I’m a firm believer that effective leadership starts with a relationship and a commitment to being uncomfortable. 

🎊 I’ve recently become a featured presenter for @elevateyourclassroom thanks to my friends at @kindergartensmorgasboard . You can catch me in Connecticut at the end of the month, in Dallas next June, or in Phoenix next July. This has been one of the highlights of my career and the happiest I’ve been in this profession. The conferences are 🔥 and it has truly been life-changing. Hope to see you on the road! 

📓 I serve as an Adjunct Faculty Member for Marquette University’s College of Education. I work with seniors completing their final literacy practicum course. It is such an eye-opening and humbling experience that brings me a lot of joy. 

🌱 I name my houseplants after strong female characters in TV or famous drag queens. Ha! I have a huge passion for TV and music stats, so if you ever need to know how well your fav’s recent album did on the charts, I’m your guy. 😂 

💕 Well, what else? Say hi 👋🏻!
